[STAGE 1 — LABORATORY-SPECIFIC ADDENDUM]

This addendum is appended to the Stage 1 base prompt ONLY when the scene is
classified as "lab" (research / chemistry / biology / pharma-GMP / physics /
optics / metrology / electronics R&D). It OVERRIDES the base prompt where they
conflict; the base prompt still applies for everything else.

WHY THIS ADDENDUM EXISTS
Vision models systematically under-estimate laboratory room dimensions and
mis-classify the upper "reagent shelf / divider rack" of a double-deck lab
bench as a small surface-top accessory. Both errors break downstream geometry.

==============================================================================
A. ROOM-SCALE PRIORS FOR LAB SCENES (USE THESE BEFORE GUESSING)
==============================================================================

A.0 OUTPUT-FIELD AXIS CONTRACT (READ THIS FIRST — STRICT)
The downstream pipeline interprets `estimated_dimensions = "W m × D m"`
along FIXED world axes that are tied to the image, not to the room's
"long edge". You MUST follow this contract:

  - W (the FIRST number) = horizontal extent of the room in the image.
      It is the east-west span, between the LEFT (west) wall and the
      RIGHT (east) wall, measured in metres.
  - D (the SECOND number) = vertical extent of the room in the image.
      It is the north-south span, between the TOP (north) wall and the
      BOTTOM (south) wall, measured in metres.

This means:
  - A room that looks WIDER than TALL in the image  →  W > D.
  - A room that looks TALLER than WIDE in the image  →  D > W.
  - If you mentally measured "long edge" first, you must still figure
    out which IMAGE AXIS that long edge runs along, and place it in
    the correct slot (W or D).

PIXEL-RATIO SANITY CHECK (perform this every time before returning)
  1. Identify the four interior wall corners of the room in the image.
  2. Measure the horizontal pixel span (px_W) of the room's interior
     floor area, and the vertical pixel span (px_D).
  3. The ratio you write MUST satisfy BOTH conditions:
       (a) Same orientation:  (W > D) ⇔ (px_W > px_D), i.e. they cannot
           disagree on which side is longer.
       (b) Approximate match:  | (W/D) / (px_W/px_D) − 1 |  <  0.30
           (the metric ratio may differ from the pixel ratio by ≤ 30 %).
  4. If your draft inverts the orientation (room is visibly wider than
     tall in the image, but you wrote D > W), SWAP W and D before
     returning. Do NOT keep an inverted ratio "because the long edge
     felt like the depth".
  5. NOTE: Many lab images are rendered in an isometric / 3-quarter
     perspective rather than a strict orthographic top-down. The pixel
     ratio is therefore only an APPROXIMATE prior — small deviations
     (within ±30 %) are normal, but a flipped orientation is NOT.

A.1 STANDARD LAB FURNITURE DIMENSIONS (use as scale references)
- Standard wall-side lab bench:        L 2.4 m, D 0.75 m, H 0.9 m
- Long wall-side lab bench:            L 3.6 m, D 0.75 m
- Island lab bench (double-sided):     L 2.4–4.8 m, D 1.5 m, H 0.9 m
- Fume hood:                           W 1.5–1.8 m, D 0.8 m, H 2.2 m
- Biosafety cabinet:                   W 1.2–1.8 m, D 0.8 m, H 2.0 m
- Lab stool:                           seat 0.4 m, total H 0.6–0.8 m
- Office chair (lab use):              0.6 × 0.6 × 0.9 m
- Standard interior door:              W 0.9 m
- Optical table:                       W 1.2–2.4 m, L 1.8–3.6 m
- Equipment rack / chromatography unit: W 0.6 m, D 0.6 m, H 1.8–2.0 m

A.2 LAB CIRCULATION RULES (these govern minimum room footprint)
- Aisle between two parallel benches (people working back-to-back):  ≥ 1.5 m
- Aisle between a bench and a wall:                                  ≥ 1.0 m
- Clearance in front of a fume hood (operator + cart):               ≥ 1.5 m
- Clearance in front of a chair pulled out from a bench:             ≥ 0.8 m
- Emergency egress aisle in any GMP / safety-rated lab:              ≥ 1.2 m

A.3 ROOM-SIZE TYPICAL FOOTPRINTS (TARGETS — TREAT AS GUIDES, NOT FLOORS)
The table below is given as `long_edge × short_edge` (NOT W × D), because
it only describes the room's footprint in metric terms and is independent
of how the room is oriented in the image. Once you pick an entry from
this table, you still have to decide which side of the room is the
horizontal (W) one and which is the vertical (D) one in the image, using
A.0's pixel-ratio sanity check.

The numbers below are TYPICAL footprints for compact / small-to-medium
academic and R&D labs, NOT absolute floors. A real lab can be ~1 m
smaller on either side if circulation is tight. Bias DOWN, not up, when
the image is ambiguous.

| Lab type                                       | long × short typical |
|------------------------------------------------|----------------------|
| Single wall-bench teaching / prep lab          |  ~5 m × 4 m          |
| One island bench + perimeter benches           |  ~6 m × 5 m          |
| Two parallel island benches (research lab)     |  ~8 m × 6 m          |
| GMP / pharma QC lab with hoods + prep benches  | ~10 m × 7 m          |
| Optics / laser lab with full optical tables    | ~10 m × 7 m          |
| Metrology / precision-measurement lab          |  ~8 m × 6 m          |

STRICT DEFINITION — "TWO PARALLEL ISLAND BENCHES"
Use the "two parallel island" row ONLY if BOTH of the following are true:
  (i)  You can clearly identify TWO benches that are each DOUBLE-SIDED
       workstations (i.e., usable from both long sides, no wall behind),
       each with length ≥ 2.4 m and depth ≥ 1.2 m.
  (ii) There is a central aisle between the two benches that is wider
       than ~1.2 m and clearly used for circulation (no furniture in it).

A common error is to read "one central island bench + one wall-side
bench bank" as "two parallel islands". That layout is NOT two islands;
it is "One island bench + perimeter benches" → use the smaller
~6 m × 5 m typical, not ~8 m × 6 m.

⚠️  A "4 m × 4 m" estimate for any lab that genuinely contains TWO
   parallel island benches (per the strict definition above) is almost
   always wrong. Walk through the math:
     two islands (1.2 m deep each) = 2.4 m
     center aisle between them      = 1.2 m
     side aisles to walls (×2)      = 1.6 m  (0.8 m each, tight)
     total minimum short edge       = 5.2 m
   plus long edge: each island ≥ 2.4 m + 0.8 m clearance on both ends
   ≥ 4.0 m. The TYPICAL value listed above (~8 m × 6 m) already builds
   in a small extra margin on top of the tight minimum; do NOT inflate
   beyond it without visible evidence of a third bench bank or a full
   set of equipment racks on a separate wall.

A.4 SCALE REFERENCE PROCEDURE (do this BEFORE writing estimated_dimensions)
1. Find at least ONE object whose real-world width you know:
   - door (0.9 m), lab bench short side (0.75 m), office chair (0.6 m),
     fume hood width (1.5 m), lab stool footprint (0.4 m).
2. Measure that object in pixels in the top-down image.
3. Compute pixels-per-metre.
4. Measure room interior horizontal pixel span (px_W) and vertical pixel
   span (px_D). Divide each by pixels-per-metre → metric W and D.
5. Round to the nearest 0.5 m (do NOT systematically round up or down —
   either direction is acceptable; over-estimating is just as bad as
   under-estimating because it cascades into oversized furniture and
   wasted floor area).
6. Cross-check against table A.3, treating your two numbers as
   long_edge = max(W, D) and short_edge = min(W, D):
   - Table A.3 values are TYPICAL footprints, NOT hard floors. If your
     measured estimate is within ±1.5 m of the typical row for the
     visible lab layout, KEEP your measured value — do not snap up to
     the table value.
   - If your measured estimate is MORE THAN 1.5 m ABOVE the typical
     row on either side AND you cannot clearly identify a third bench
     bank / extra equipment row / wide circulation aisle that justifies
     the extra space, you over-estimated. Re-measure with a different
     reference object and shrink toward the typical value.
   - If your measured estimate is MORE THAN 1.5 m BELOW the typical
     row on either side AND circulation requirements in A.2 cannot fit
     in that footprint, you under-estimated. Re-measure and grow toward
     the typical value, recording the cue in `scale_reference_objects`.
   - When two measurements bracket the typical value, prefer the
     smaller one. Over-estimating wastes floor area and cascades into
     oversized furniture and empty-looking renders.
7. Re-check A.0's PIXEL-RATIO SANITY CHECK:
   - The first number you write (W) must correspond to the horizontal
     image extent; the second number (D) to the vertical extent.
   - If your long_edge happens to run vertically in the image, it must
     go into the D slot, not the W slot.
8. In `estimated_dimensions`, write a string like  "9 m × 7 m"  (use ×
   not x). The first number is W (horizontal/east-west), the second is
   D (vertical/north-south).

A.5 VISUAL-ARTIFACT WARNINGS SPECIFIC TO LABS
- Many lab images are rendered with extra-narrow aspect ratios (the bench
  zone fills the image edge-to-edge). Do NOT shrink the room to bench size.
  The room MUST include the operator-aisle area on both sides of every island.
- Stainless-steel floor reflections and grid-tile patterns can look like
  small-tile residential floors; do not infer a "small bedroom-sized" room
  from the tile spacing alone.
- Many lab images use an isometric / 3-quarter perspective camera rather
  than a strict orthographic top-down. In that view the FAR side of the
  room (e.g. the north wall) is visually compressed compared to the
  near side. Do NOT take pixel measurements at face value on the far
  side; prefer reference objects sitting in the MIDDLE of the room for
  pixels-per-metre calibration.

A.6 UPPER-BOUND SANITY CHECK (PREVENT OVER-ESTIMATION)
After writing estimated_dimensions, verify it is not absurdly large:
- If your estimate exceeds 12 m × 10 m (≥ 120 m²), check that AT LEAST
  ONE of the following is true:
    (a) You can count ≥ 3 separate workstations / bench banks / island
        units / fume-hood bays in the image.
    (b) The long-edge pixel span divided by the typical bench pixel
        span is ≥ 5 (i.e., the room is at least five bench-widths long).
- If NEITHER (a) nor (b) holds, you over-estimated. Re-run A.4 with a
  different scale reference and shrink the estimate. A typical
  single-island research lab is ~6 m × 5 m, NOT 10 m × 8 m. A typical
  two-island research lab is ~8 m × 6 m, NOT 12 m × 10 m.

==============================================================================
B. LAB BENCH STRUCTURE: DOUBLE-DECK / OVERSIZED ISLAND DETECTION
==============================================================================

B.1 WHAT A DOUBLE-DECK LAB BENCH LOOKS LIKE FROM ABOVE
A double-deck lab bench is ONE physical piece of furniture but has:
- a lower WORKTOP (the surface people work on, knee-to-elbow height ≈ 0.9 m), and
- an UPPER REAGENT SHELF (a horizontal board running along the bench centerline,
  supported by 2–4 vertical posts, height ≈ 1.2–1.5 m), often with
  bottles, racks, small instruments sitting ON the upper shelf.

In a top-down image the upper shelf appears as a NARROW HORIZONTAL STRIP
running along the LONG CENTER LINE of the bench. It commonly looks like:
- a "central divider rack" cutting the bench into two operator sides, OR
- a row of tall thin objects (reagent bottles, glassware) lined up exactly
  along the bench centerline.

B.2 CRITICAL CLASSIFICATION RULE — DO NOT SPLIT A DOUBLE-DECK BENCH
If you see a long, narrow strip of "objects" running exactly along the
centerline of an island lab bench, those are MOST LIKELY items resting on
the upper shelf of a double-deck bench. The upper shelf itself is PART OF
THE BENCH STRUCTURE, not a separate surface object.

❌ DO NOT do this:
   - Emit the bench as one major floor object
   - Then emit "Central Divider Rack" as a minor surface object on top of it
   - Then emit reagent bottles as surface objects on top of the rack

✅ DO this instead:
   - Emit the bench as ONE major floor object whose `name` makes the
     double-deck nature clear (e.g., "West Island Lab Bench (double-deck)").
   - Add the OPTIONAL field `structure_hint` to that object entry:
       "structure_hint": "double_deck"
   - Items VISIBLY sitting on the UPPER shelf may still be emitted as surface
     objects parented to the bench, but their semantics is "on upper shelf",
     reflected in the object name (e.g., "Reagent Bottle on upper shelf").
   - The "rack / divider" itself is NOT a separate object. It is bench
     structure.

B.3 OVERSIZED-ISLAND DETECTION
If a single island bench visibly extends across more than ~60% of the room
length, OR is clearly longer than 2.4 m relative to the standard scale, it
is an "oversized island". Add the OPTIONAL field:
    "structure_hint": "oversized_island"
to that object entry. Stage 3 will use this to allow long composite-piece
geometry (up to ~4.8 m) instead of clamping to 2.4 m.

B.4 COMBINED HINT
A bench that is BOTH double-deck AND oversized → use:
    "structure_hint": "double_deck_oversized"

B.5 STRUCTURE_HINT FIELD CONTRACT
- Field name:   "structure_hint"
- Position:     inside an object entry of object_hierarchy.
- Type:         string. Allowed values:
                  "double_deck" | "oversized_island" | "double_deck_oversized"
- Optional:     yes (omit when none of the above apply)
- ONLY emit on objects with category=="major" and placement_type=="floor".
- ONLY emit on lab bench / island workstation objects. Do NOT emit on
  fume hoods, biosafety cabinets, optical tables, equipment racks.

==============================================================================
C. LAB OBJECT-CATEGORY ADJUSTMENTS
==============================================================================

C.1 CATEGORY OVERRIDES (these supersede the base prompt for lab scenes)
- "lab bench / island workstation"           → category = "major", placement = "floor"
- "fume hood / biosafety cabinet"            → category = "major", placement = "floor"
- "chemical / solvent storage cabinet"       → category = "major", placement = "floor"
- "equipment rack / chromatography stack"    → category = "major", placement = "floor"
- "optical table"                            → category = "major", placement = "floor"
- "lab stool"                                → category = "major", placement = "floor"
- "glassware cluster (flasks/beakers)"       → category = "minor", placement = "surface"
- "hot plate / stirrer / balance / centrifuge" → category = "minor", placement = "surface"
- "reagent bottle / spray bottle / sample"   → category = "minor", placement = "surface"
- "safety shower / eyewash"                  → category = "major", placement = "floor"

C.2 LAB-WALL OBJECTS
Most labs have FEW wall-mounted decorative items but DO often have:
- a clock above the door
- a fire-safety / hazard pictogram poster
- a wall-mounted gas / electric panel
- a wall-mounted phone or intercom
- a wall-mounted whiteboard near the door
Emit visible ones with placement_type="wall". DO NOT fabricate framed art
on lab walls if the image shows bare painted walls.

==============================================================================
C.3 LAB WORKTOP / SHELF SURFACE CLUTTER SWEEP (DOWNSTREAM PIPELINE REQUIRES THIS)
==============================================================================

Vision models often over-list clutter on the **central island / focal bench**
and under-list the **same class of clutter** on **other benches**
(perimeter wall benches, south/north bench runs, secondary workstations).

You MUST treat EACH distinct lab bench worktop AND EACH visibly cluttered
upper shelf (consistent with B.2 / structure_hint) as its own scan target:

1. **Enumeration targets** (emit as `category="minor"`, `placement_type="surface"`,
   `parent_object` = the bench / shelf object's object_id):
   - Pipette racks / tip boxes; tube racks; well plates / microplates
   - Clusters of flasks / beakers / bottles / solvent wash bottles
   - Small instruments: balances, hotplates, stirrers, vortex, timers
   - PCs / monitors / keyboards / small lab notebooks / trays / mats
   - Each **visually separate** cluster gets its **own** object row (do not merge
     "everything on the south bench" into one blob unless it truly reads as a
     single indivisible smear).

2. **Multi-bench parity (mandatory)**: After drafting `object_hierarchy`, compare
   EVERY pair of bench/shelf surfaces that **look similarly busy** in the image.
   If Bench A has ≥ N surface minors and Bench B shows comparable tabletop
   complexity but has ≪ N, **re-scan Bench B** at higher magnification and add
   the missing minors. Do NOT rationalize away south/perimeter benches because
   attention stayed on the center of the image.

3. **Still obey B.2**: Do not invent a fake "divider rack" object; upper-shelf
   geometry belongs to the bench's structure_hint. Items **resting on** that
   shelf are still valid surface minors parented to the bench.

==============================================================================
D. FINAL LAB-SPECIFIC VALIDATION CHECK
==============================================================================
Before returning, verify in this order:
1. AXIS CONTRACT (A.0): the FIRST number in estimated_dimensions is W
   (horizontal/east-west); the SECOND is D (vertical/north-south).
   - The orientation matches the image: a visually wider room has W > D,
     a visually taller room has D > W.
   - The pixel ratio sanity check (A.0 step 3) holds within ±30 %.
2. TYPICAL FOOTPRINT (A.3): treating the two numbers as long_edge /
   short_edge, each is within ±1.5 m of the typical row for the visible
   lab layout. In particular, do NOT declare "two parallel islands"
   unless the strict definition in A.3 is met (one central island +
   a wall-side bench is "one island bench + perimeter benches",
   not two islands). When the image is ambiguous between two adjacent
   rows, pick the SMALLER row.
3. UPPER BOUND (A.6): if your estimate exceeds 12 m × 10 m, you can
   count ≥ 3 separate bench banks OR the long edge is ≥ 5 bench-widths;
   otherwise you have over-estimated.
4. Every island bench with a visible upper-shelf strip has either
   structure_hint="double_deck" or "double_deck_oversized".
5. No object named "Central Divider Rack" / "Reagent Shelf" exists as a
   separate `surface` object that supports other items — those have been
   absorbed into the parent bench's structure_hint.
6. Aisles between islands and walls are wide enough to satisfy A.2; if
   not, the room must be at least the A.3 minimum.
7. **Surface clutter parity (C.3)**: For each major lab bench / island /
   cluttered upper shelf, count `placement_type="surface"` minors whose
   `parent_object` points to it. If two surfaces look similarly busy in the
   image but counts differ by an order of magnitude, fix before returning.
